<DOC><DOCNO>WSJ900814-0017</DOCNO><DOCID>900814-0017.</DOCID><HL>   Con Ed Personnel   Faced With Bribery,   Extortion Charges</HL><DATE>08/14/90</DATE><SO>WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), PAGE C8</SO><CO>   ED LABOR</CO><IN>ELECTRIC UTILITIES (ELC)</IN><GV>LABOR DEPARTMENT (LBR)</GV><LP>   WASHINGTON -- The Labor Department's inspector generalcharged 17 former and current Consolidated Edison Co.employees with bribery and extortion involving cash from ConEd customers, electrical contractors and others.   The inspector general's office of labor racketeering filedcriminal complaints in federal and state courts in New York.The complaints alleged that the Con Ed employees extortedcash in return for, among other things, overlooking safetyhazards such as natural gas leaks, allowing illegal gas andelectrical hookups to go unreported, and expediting theproviding of gas or electrical service.</LP><TEXT>   The investigation is part of a probe by thelabor-racketeering office into corruption in the New Yorkconstruction industry, said Stephen Cossu, the office's NewYork agent-in-charge.   Complaints were filed in federal district court inBrooklyn charging extortion and fraud against seven personsof Con Ed's Bedford/Bushwick branch, including two managers.   Ten people including a supervisor were charged in statecourt with extortion and bribery, including allowing illegalhookups for Manhattan customers, at a restaurant, auto repairshop, laundromat and an apartment building, and permittingdelays in repairs of gas leaks at an apartment building and arestaurant.</TEXT></DOC>